I don't know how to do the arithmetic, but I can provide a simple example.
Let's say you have a set of points and a set of lines, and you want to store the intersection points.
You could keep the intersection points as a list of the intersections, and use a hash function to get the corresponding line when you need it.
Even better, you could store the lines as objects, and use a hash function to get the corresponding intersection point when you need it.
The advantage of this is that the intersection points will be stored as separate objects, independent of the lines.
The worst case time complexity is O(n*m) with intersection points as elements in a set.
An advantage of this approach is that you can use every type of data structure you want, and you can also store any number of objects, and not just one intersection point.
I've done this in the past, and it works well.

A:

You could use a combination hash table and array:
class Point {
    int x, y;
    /* ... */
}

class Line {
    Point firstPoint, secondPoint;
    /* ... */
}

class Intersection {
    Point intersectionPoint;
    /* ... */
}

Then you can use the following structures to store them:
class PointArray {
    int num;
    Point *array; /* array[num] contains the points */
}

class LineArray {
    int num;
    Line *array; /* array[num] contains the lines */
}

class IntersectionArray {
    int num;
    Intersection *array; /* array[num] contains the intersections */
}

To get a Point from the intersection, the intersection point is just a member variable in the Intersection class.  To get a Line from the intersection, the intersection point is a member variable in the Intersection class.
The time complexity for searching a Point is O(1), the time complexity for searching a Line is O(logN) (where N is the number of existing Lines), and the time complexity for searching an Intersection is O(1), as I assume you can't store a Line in an Intersection and iterate through all the Intersections to find the intersection point.

