You can't: rst files are plain text, and URLs are just text with special characters. I don't know of any rst package that will allow you to format URLs.
However, if you are interested in creating an rst file that can be served by the server (like the one in this question), you can write a custom <link> tag in the <head> section of your document. For example:
<head>
  <style>
    .no-href {
      color: #F00;
    }
    .href {
      color: #0F0;
    }
  </style>

  <link rel="stylesheet" href="//example.com/style.css" type="text/css" />

  <style type="text/css">
    a[href="http://www.example.com/foo"] {
      color: #CC00;
    }
    a[href="http://www.example.com/bar"] {
      color: #0F0;
    }
  </style>
</head>

In this example, all links have the class no-href, but only the links with the href attribute have the class href.

